english:
  title: Reflections
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Heaven and earth—the great furnace of creation,
    How laborious the casting of all things!
    Principle presides as master,
    Qi divides them into their kinds.

    The rare are scarce as a unicorn's horn,
    The common—are they not countless as ox hairs?
    Humaneness and righteousness become our daily bread,
    Rites and laws our robes of office.

    Resplendent, they shine across the world—
    Where then can our brief lives escape?
  footnotes:
    - The 'great furnace' (洪爐) is a metaphor for the creative force of the cosmos, suggesting the primal chaos from which all forms emerge.
    - 'In Neo-Confucian philosophy, ''Principle'' (理) and ''Qi'' (氣) are the fundamental complementary forces: Principle is the ordering cosmic pattern, while Qi is the vital material force through which it manifests.'
    - The contrast between the rare (unicorn's horn) and the common (ox hairs) reflects on how virtue and its absence are distributed unequally among people.
    - Humaneness, righteousness, rites, and laws represent the cardinal virtues of Confucian ethics—the spiritual and moral sustenance that should guide human life.
